<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n53050d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53050d">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53050d"> 50(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> van der Berg</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[We have almost completely lost a case for the notion of &lsquo;whence&rsquo;, and therefore a particular preposition has been created to denote this direction, i.e. &lsquo;from&rsquo; &hellip; most probably derived (cf. Greek <i>apo</i>) from the adverb &lsquo;above&rsquo;, that is (seen from below) the answer to the question, Whence?; from above, &lsquo;abe&rsquo;. In Switzerland one can still find such names as &lsquo;Ab der Fluh&rsquo;, corresponding to our &lsquo;<mark>Von der Fluh</mark>&rsquo;.]</font> <small> Fritz Mauthner, <a name="FMBK1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FMBK1"><cite title="source">Beitr&auml;ge zu einer Kritik der Sprache.</cite></a> 3 vols (1901-2) III 111</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Van der Berg is a Dutch name. </mm> </dd></dl>
